TABEXP TOGGLE TAB EXPANSION MODE
	The @ME.HLX^INEDTA[Tab Expansion] setting will be changed for current editing
session only.
TABSPAC CHANGE TAB SPACING
	Tab spacing determines the interval between two successive tab stops.
The default @ME.HLX^FE_TAB[Install, Filename Extensions] setting will be changed for current
editing session only.
DISPLTABS DISPLAY TABS TOGGLE
	This is the same toggle as in @ME.HLX^DSPTABS[Menu, Layout]. Note that if your current
@ME.HLX^INEDTA[Tab Expansion] setting is Spaces then tabs will not be displayed even if they
are actually present in your file.
INS_IN_TABLE INSERTING TABS IN A TABLE
	You will hardly ever need to do this. If your file is split into
columns starting at fixed positions then you can adjust the @ME.HLX^EDFMTLIN[format line]
so that tab stops would correspond to column starting positions. Having done
that, you can slightly compress your file substituting a single tab character
for trailing spaces in each column.
COMPRESS COMPRESS LEADING SPACES
	In a structured programming language, statements are usually indented,
their offset from start of line corresponding to their nesting level. You can
reduce the size of your program file if you replace the leading spaces by tab
characters, having set the proper tab spacing. A typical program would shrink
to two-thirds of its initial volume due to that operation.
TABS_TO_SPACES CONVERTING TABS TO SPACES
	Multi-Edit has great flexibility in handling tab characters. But
sometimes you would be happier if there were no tabs in your file, for other
programs may treat them in a different way. If you run ^BConvert tabs to spaces^b
from this menu, the text in your file will look exactly the same way as
before, but all white space will be filled with spaces (ASCII 32).
MODFMTLIN MODIFYING THE FORMAT LINE
	If you reply "Yes", and the first tab stop in your current format line
does not correspond to the currently set Tab spacing, then the format line
will be modified so that the tab stops will be every ^B<Tab spacing>^b columns.
KEY_ASS CURRENT MULTI-EDIT KEY ASSIGNMENT
	This menu provides an easy way to learn about the keyboard shortcuts
available in Multi-Edit. From this menu, you can run any of the macros
available in EDIT mode. Hit ^B<CR>^b to build the command line to invoke the
selected macro. You can then edit the command line, possibly adding or
changing command-line parameters.
	NOTE. You cannot run @MACRO.HLX^CMDTOKEY[Commands directly assigned to a key] from this
menu.
